['"go"', 'I think one of the hardest things I had to learn about ML was that ML won't always give you the best solution... especially with very classical kinds of data like time series. With time series, I always had better success with Exponential Smoothing or Season Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average models than with something like a Long Short-Term Memory/Recurrent Neural Network model even if I spent a ton of time tuning hyperparameters, dropout rates inside the cells, etc. Couldn't get it anywhere close to the classic methods in terms of lowering the average error rate of guessing the next step. In real life, it's rare that you have enough data for the model to actually get better results than those other two methods. There are a few free papers online comparing ML to classical methods for time series data if anyone reading this is interested. Definitely consider other options! Just because the phrases "Machine Learning" and "Neural Network" get the higher-ups excited when they hear it doesn't mean it's the only choice you have!', 'I think front-end development will be replaced by ML models that generate front-end code. What do you think?', 'I feel the same way! The end of DL may be interesting but the process is quite boring and is hard for non-methematics backgroud people. But I kind of have to learn DL for my research :(
Still waiting for next trend in data analysis field!', 'i play call of duty while its training', 'Because you suck ?', 'Regardless of whether he had any basics or not, I think it is very important to recognize that the role of an ML Engineer or a data scientist is very different to that one of a backend or software dev. It is important to recognize that if you already enjoy your work in one of those roles, finding an opportunity that allows you to experiment with doing data analysis or even a deep neural net and keep your common responsibilities in another web dev role is near impossible.

To learn ML or DL and apply it correctly you will most likely end up doing a career swap.', 'Do not confuse being a statistician and being a programmer :p', "neuralnetworksanddeeplearning.com is a great way to learn the basic math behind machine learning. In order to fully understand machine learning you need to be comfortable with the relevant math. The kind of people who go into machine learning are the people who are usually into math and not into software engineering much. I think the reason that many people follow the machine learning hype and get disappointed comes from not understanding that machine learning is just a tool - its a means to and end and not an end in itself. There are many cool advancements in machine learning like reinforcement learning where you make the model learn to play video games or in the future make the model drive a car on its own (Tesla still doesn't fully utilize reinforcement learning) but ML is very math heavy (for software engineers) but not so much for math majors.", '8:41 "Linear Regression, that's too basic"

["*Why did he add 1 to data_matrix at @**8:10**?* 
Read ahead if you're confused about why he did that. I've tried to explain the process.

Let's track it from the beginning:
Here the hypothesis equation (or linear regression equation) is:
hŒò(x) = w*x +b  
This means that we have to multiply the input (denoted by 'x') by the weight (denoted by 'w') and then add the bias term (denoted by 'b') to the product.
During matrix multiplication, we take the first row of the data_matrix (x) and multiply it with the first column of the parameter_vector (w).
hŒò(x) = (0.25)*x + (-40)
To obtain the result as 0.25 * element of data_matrix + (-40) we need to keep a term as 1.
We can write it as @9:30 or like this:
data_vector  
[2104     1]   *   [0.25
                            -40]
The multiplication would be done in the following way: (2014*0.25) + (1 * -40)           {first row element of data matrix * first column element of parameter_vecotr + second element of data_matrix * second element of parameter_vector}
If you analyze the multiplication result, it is the same as:  x*0.25 - 40        {hŒò(x) = w*x +b, where w is 0.25 and b is -40 i.e. hŒò(x) = x*0.25 - 40}

At @9:30, the same thing is written in a slightly different way:
[1      2104]   *    [-40 
                             0.25]
The result is: 1*(-40) + 2104 * 0.25, which is same as 2104*0.25 - 40  {hŒò(x) = x*0.25 - 40}
So we are adding a 1 before or after the data (depending on how we write the parameter_vector) in data_matrix in order to correctly form the equation: hŒò(x) = x*0.25 - 40.

Please feel free to ask if any of this does not make sense.", 'can anyone help me with 7:28 on why we made a matrix [1 2104] and multiplied with the parameters?', "Isn't this doing a ton of unnecessary multiplication by 1? ['Hi nice bit of coding but there is a number of errors in your networking description.  Firstly the modem is not where your public address will sit it will be on the wan interface of the router and the router is in fact firewall as it will hide the private addresses behind the public address.  

You are dealing with tcp ports the is  65535 ports full list https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_TCP_and_UDP_port_numbers

And the number you are seeing with the received message on the server is in fact the source port. 

Also you would not run your server on the modem it would be run inside your net work and using Nat you would forward connections to the server  via the router but this would be bad idea on a home internet connection as the router will not be secure enough as you normally what to this via a DMZ.', "Thank you Tim really you have helped me a lot.I was actually stuck on how to connect the devices over internet. The lowest 1024 port numbers identify the most commonly used services, and you are not supposed to use them for another service but the default.
For example, 22 for SSH, 80 for HTTP, 443 for HTTPS...
The remaining are used for general purpose. BUT, if you use some well known application, it can have default ports over the 1024 mentioned.
For example, 3389 is used for Microsoft Terminal Server (RDP), 3306 is used for MySQL, and so on.', 'Hi Tim
